m_DescList: Sometimes we need to describe sets of characters, like the set of English vowels.
<color=#3173FF>[]</color> can represent items from an enumerated character set.
For example, <color=#3173FF>[</color><color=#AB2800>aeiou</color><color=#3173FF>]</color> matches elements in <color=#3c3cff>Hello World</color>:

Similarly, <color=#05C3BA>(</color><color=#AB2800>a</color><color=#05C3BA>|</color><color=#AB2800>e</color><color=#05C3BA>|</color><color=#AB2800>i</color><color=#05C3BA>|</color><color=#AB2800>o</color><color=#05C3BA>|</color><color=#AB2800>u</color><color=#05C3BA>)</color> can match elements in <color=#3c3cff>Hello World</color>:
<color=#3173FF>[</color><color=#AB2800>a</color><color=#3173FF>-</color><color=#AB2800>f</color><color=#3173FF>]</color> represents matching from character "a" to character "f",
- the hyphen here no longer indicates negation, but denotes the range from character "a" to "f".

For example, <color=#3173FF>[</color><color=#AB2800>a</color><color=#3173FF>-</color><color=#AB2800>c0</color><color=#3173FF>-</color><color=#AB2800>2</color><color=#3173FF>]</color> means <color=#3173FF>[</color><color=#AB2800>abc012</color><color=#3173FF>]</color>, matching elements in <color=#3c3cff>abcd01234</color>:
